{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"54c82c94-e185-435b-8f83-d2617bce519e","content":"I don't see a `.dmp` file in the current directory. If you can place it here, I can try basic analysis, but honestly **this environment isn't ideal for crash dump analysis** — it lacks the specialized tools.\n\nHere's how to analyze your dump effectively:\n\n### Recommended Tools\n\n1. **WinDbg / WinDbg Preview** (Windows) — best option:\n   ```\n   .loadby sos clr        # .NET Framework\n   .loadby sos coreclr    # .NET Core+\n   !clrstack              # managed call stack\n   !pe                    # print last exception\n   !dumpheap -stat        # heap summary\n   ```\n\n2. **`dotnet-dump`** (cross-platform CLI):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   dotnet-dump analyze <your-file.dmp>\n   ```\n   Then inside the REPL:\n   - `clrstack` — managed stack trace\n   - `pe` — last exception details\n   - `threads` — list all threads\n   - `dumpheap -stat` — heap overview\n\n3. **Visual Studio** — open the `.dmp` directly, click **\"Debug with Managed Only\"**.\n\n### Quick Triage Steps\n1. Run `pe` (print exception) to find the exception type and message\n2. Run `clrstack` to see where it crashed\n3. Check `threads` for deadlocks or thread pool exhaustion\n\nWould you like me to help interpret specific output from any of these tools, or assist with something else?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8abbc27b-b92e-4f84-a053-e912d9832e1b","outputTokens":367,"requestId":"5FC0:27C56C:DEA139:102D62A:69EACC3E"},"id":"c9fd0149-e61b-48fd-9a73-e78a3afe548b","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:50:01.884Z","parentId":"0f310f1e-87e9-4ec4-b3da-f1eae6dafd55"}
